Base:Descriptions.Base:Description: billiard table

The billiard table is about nine feet in length and and has been set at a diagonal in the center of the room to give ample space around the table for ease of shooting the billiard balls. The table itself is made of dark mahogany and is covered with a green felt lining across the playing area. At the table's edges are raised, four inch railings as a guard against balls rolling from the table. Short cue sticks and three billiard balls accompany the table. The goal of the game is to set a predetermined number. You then aim your cue ball, at either the white or spotted balls, so that it hits both the other player's ball and the red ball in one shot. The player who reaches the predetermined number first wins.

white cue
The white ball is made of solid oak, it's 2 inches in diameter, and weighs 12 ounces.
The white cue ball has a visible 1 printed on it.
spotted cue
The spotted cue ball is made of solid oak, is 2 inches in diameter, and weighs 12 ounces.
The spotted ball has a visible 2 printed on it.
red ball
The red ball is made of solid oak, is 2 inches in diameter, and weighs 12 ounces.
The red ball has a visible 2 printed on it.
centered legs
The support of this table is a thick central cluster of legs. Six cedar legs have been constructed back to back to provide a sturdy foundation.
The support of this table is a thick central cluster of legs.
pale green felt lining
Pale green felt has been stretched across the playing surface and tacked firmly into place to provide a cushioned, yet level surface for the balls to easily roll across.
The pale green felt lining covers the top of the table.
raised railing
A raised, four inch railing frames the table's edges as a guard against balls rolling from the table.
The railing of the table completely encompasses the billiard table's pale blue lining.
cue stick
A short cue stick made of cedar. It tappers down to a blunted blue tip, while the thick end is varnished black and polished for a better grip when shooting.
